from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Cecillia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."],"variants":[{"name":"Cecelia","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":11,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705184,"age":21,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705185,"age":31,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Cecillia de Roelent was born in 1075, in Rhuddlan, Flintshire, Wales, her father, Robert de Roelent, was 21 and her mother, Cecily de Bassett, was 14. She married Richard de Banastre II in 1094, in Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died about 1128, in Leicestershire, England, at the age of 54."},"et":{"1075–about 1128":"1075–umbes 1128","1075–1128":"1075–1128","1095–1154":"1095–1154","1097–Male":"1097–Surnud","1099–Male":"1099–Surnud","1055–1121":"1055–1121","1061–1117":"1061–1117","about 1095":"umbes 1095","1121":"1121","1055":"1055","1099":"1099","1154":"1154","1075":"1075","1086":"1086","1097":"1097","1085":"1085","1096":"1096","1095":"1095","1094":"1094","1061":"1061","1117":"1117","1128":"1128","1106":"1106","about 1128":"umbes 1128","about 1086":"umbes 1086","about 1097":"umbes 1097","about 1099":"umbes 1099","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England","Rhuddlan, Flint, Wales":"Rhuddlan, Flintshire, Wales","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Rhuddlan, Flintshire, Wales":"Rhuddlan, Flintshire, Wales"},"fi":{"1075–about 1128":"1075–noin 1128","1075–1128":"1075–1128","1095–1154":"1095–1154","1097–Male":"1097–Kuollut","1099–Male":"1099–Kuollut","1055–1121":"1055–1121","1061–1117":"1061–1117","about 1095":"noin 1095","1121":"1121","1055":"1055","1099":"1099","1154":"1154","1075":"1075","1086":"1086","1097":"1097","1085":"1085","1096":"1096","1095":"1095","1094":"1094","1061":"1061","1117":"1117","1128":"1128","1106":"1106","about 1128":"noin 1128","about 1086":"noin 1086","about 1097":"n